# Background

## Diverticulitis of colon (without mention of hemorrhage)
Diverticulitis is a condition that occurs when small, bulging pouches (diverticula) in the digestive tract become inflamed or infected. Diverticula are pouches that bulge outward from the colon, which is the last part of the digestive tract.

## Abscess of intestine
An intestinal abscess is a pus-filled pocket of tissue that forms in the intestines.

## Multiple sclerosis
Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system).

## Scoliosis [and kyphoscoliosis], idiopathic
Scoliosis is a sideways curvature of the spine that most often is diagnosed in adolescents.

## Unspecified essential hypertension
High blood pressure (hypertension) is a common condition in which the long-term force of the blood against your artery walls is high enough that it may eventually cause health problems, such as heart disease.

## Epilepsy, unspecified, without mention of intractable epilepsy
Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

## Percutaneous abdominal drainage
Percutaneous drainage is a procedure to remove fluid that has built up in the abdomen.

# Background

## Oligohydramnios
Oligohydramnios is a condition where there is not enough amniotic fluid surrounding the baby during pregnancy.

### Causes
Oligohydramnios occurs in about 4% of pregnancies. Causes include:
- Birth defects that affect kidney function
- High blood pressure in the mother
- Problems with the placenta
- Premature rupture of the membranes (also called the water breaking too early)
- Problems with the development of the baby
- Problems with the mother's health, such as preeclampsia and chronic hypertension
- Problems with the mother's kidneys
- Twins or more

### Symptoms
Oligohydramnios is often discovered during a routine ultrasound exam.

### Diagnosis
The health care provider will do a complete history and physical exam. Tests that may be done include:
- Amniotic fluid volume
- Fetal monitoring
- Ultrasound

### Treatment
Treatment depends on the cause of the condition.
If the oligohydramnios is severe and the baby is far enough along, the health care provider may suggest inducing labor and delivery.

The authors report a case of a 45-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse who presented with a 2-month history of progressive dyspnea and cough. Chest radiography showed bilateral diffuse interstitial infiltrates. The patient was treated with antibiotics and steroids without improvement. A transbronchial biopsy was performed and the histological examination showed a diffuse alveolar damage. The patient died 2 months after the onset of symptoms. The autopsy revealed a diffuse alveolar damage with a marked fibroblastic proliferation. The diagnosis of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis was made. The authors discuss the clinical, radiological and pathological features of this disease. .
The authors report a case of a 45-year-old man with a history of aortic valve replacement for aortic stenosis 10 years ago. He was admitted to our hospital because of dyspnea on exertion. Echocardiography revealed severe aortic regurgitation and aortic root dilatation. He underwent aortic valve replacement and aortic root replacement with a composite graft. The postoperative course was uneventful. .
